Claude Code is one of the best tools I've ever used. But every time a new tool becomes a daily driver, you discover weird edges that breed frustration.

Here's the one that's been driving me crazy: giving longform writing feedback through prompts is fundamentally broken.

I write "make it less corporate" and Claude removes all the personality. I write "keep my voice" and get something that sounds like a legal disclaimer trying to be casual. We go back and forth five times and I end up just rewriting it myself.

"Write it more naturally." "Less AI-slop." "Keep my voice but make it tighter."

Every time, something gets lost in translation. The feedback loop is broken at the protocol level. We're using prose to communicate edits when we should just be... editing.

Built Marginalia to fix this.

It's a small, disposable editor that hooks into Claude Code. When Claude writes a draft, Marginalia pops up. You mark up the text directly, leave short rationales on your changes if you want, and close it. The agent gets a structured diff of what you actually changed and whyâ€”without you ever leaving the CLI session.
